===Etymology===
From {{etyl|NL.}} {{term|logarithmus|lang=la}}, term coined by Scot mathematician [[w:John Napier|John Napier]] from {{etyl|grc}} {{term|λόγος||word, reason|sc=Polytonic|tr=logos|lang=grc}} and {{term|ἀριθμός||number|sc=Polytonic|tr=arithmos|lang=grc}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{mathematics}} For a number <math>x</math>, the [[power]] to which a given ''[[base]]'' number must be raised in order to obtain <math>x</math>.  Written <math>\log_b x</math>.  For example, <math>\log_{10} 1000 = 3</math> because <math>10^3 = 1000</math>.

